<F P=100> Philippines </F>
<H3> <TI>   Talks With NDF Groups, ABB Threats Reported </TI></H3>
<H4>   Government May Meet `Revisionists' </H4>
<F P=102> BK2101103994 Quezon City MALAYA in English 18 Jan 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> BK2101103994 </F>
<F P=104>  Quezon City MALAYA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Joy Gruta] </F>
  [Text] The government peace panel is willing to negotiate 
with the "revisionist faction" of the National Democratic Front 
if its talks with Netherlands-based NDF [National Democratic 
Front] leadership collapse, Ambassador Howard Dee, head of the 
panel, said yesterday. 
  Dee said the government peace panel is considering "other 
options" if the talks with NDF Jose Maria Sison and Luis 
Jalandoni failed. 
  "If the exploratory talks will not take place in the first 
quarter, we have to consider other options like opening up to 
the revisionist faction in the communist movement," Dee said. 
  Dee made the statement two days after the Alex Boncayao 
Brigade (ABB) released the names of some 345 persons marked for 
liquidation for their alleged involvement in various crimes. 
  He said the threatened new wave of assassination by the ABB 
hit squad will not affect the peace negotiations between the 
government and the NDF. 
  Dee said the ABB's threat to liquidate corrupt officials in 
the government, including police and military officials, will 
not directly affect the stalled talks with the NDF. He noted 
that the hit squad had already broken off from the mainstream 
communist movement. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

