<F P=100> Philippines </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mindanao Leaders Sign Peace Resolutions </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK2001084194 Quezon City MALAYA in English 16 Jan 94 pp 1, 3 </F>
<F P=103> BK2001084194 </F>
<F P=104>  Quezon City MALAYA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Ellen Tordesillas] </F>
  [Text] Mindanao leaders signed yesterday two resolutions 
in Malacanang to further peace in the region. 
  The first resolution expressed their support for the peace 
talks between the government and the Moro National Liberation 
Front (MNLF); the second recommended the establishment of a 
consultative mechanism between the peace panels and the Mindanao 
community. 
  Present in the meeting held Friday afternoon were Defense 
Secretary Renato de Villa; Interior Secretary Rafael Alunan 
III; Presidential Assistant for Mindanao Paul Dominguez; 
Lieutenant. General Thelmo Cunanan, Southern Command commander; 
Governor Liningding Pangandaman of the Autonomous Region of 
Muslim Mindanao; Davao City Mayor Rodrigo Duterte; and 
Representatives Maria Clara Lobregat (Laban [Party], Zamboanga) 
and Nur Jaafar (Lakas [Party], Tawi-tawi). 
  The meeting assessed the peace and order situation in 
Mindanao in the wake of the bombings perpetrated by radical 
groups, the current peace talks between the government and the 
MNLF, and the progress of the East-Asian Growth Area. 
  President Ramos told the meeting he was determined to reach 
a 
pact with MNLF rebels "in a just and honorable way without 
bloodshed." The president, however, stood pat on the 
government's position disallowing MNLF Chairman Nur Misuari from 
being escorted by 500 armed bodyguards when he entered Cotabato 
City for the signing of the cease fire agreement. 
  The signing of the cease fire agreement scheduled 11 January 
was postponed due to the MNLF's demand to provide Misuari with 
armed escorts. 

</TEXT>

