<H3> <TI>   Burma Rebel Peace Talks Venue Request Rejected </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK2101023794 Bangkok THE NATION in English 21 Jan 94 p A5 </F>
<F P=103> BK2101023794 </F>
<F P=104>  Bangkok THE NATION </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] FOREIGN Minister Prasong Sunsiri yesterday said 
Thailand would not consider the Burmese ethnic minorities' 
request to use Thailand as a venue for peace talks with the 
Rangoon ruling military junta. 
  "But if the (Burmese) government itself asked for that, we 
will consider it," Prasong told reporters. [passage omitted] 
  Prasong also refused to make a direct comment on a recent 
report that Rangoon might release opposition leader Aung San Suu 
Kyi in July this year. The minister however said that only the 
Burmese government, aware of how the world community views the 
situation in Burma, would know what it should do. [passage 
omitted] 
  The junta's powerful secretary Lt Gen Khin Nyunt said the 
legitimate period of Suu Kyi's house arrest would expire in 
July. Burma's law limits the period of house arrest to a maximum 
of five years. [passage omitted] 

