<F P=100> Thailand </F>
<H3> <TI>   Danish Aid Cut, Pressure Sought on Burma </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM2101132094 Copenhagen BERLINGSKE TIDENDE in Danish 18 Jan 
94 p 4 </F>

<F P=103> PM2101132094 </F>
<F P=104>  Copenhagen BERLINGSKE TIDENDE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Danish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Louise Fleischer report: "Too Rich for Development Aid"] </F>
  [Excerpts] Bangkok -- The Thais have become too rich to 
receive Danish development aid. Consequently Denmark will 
gradually cease aid. 
  So said Foreign Minister Niels Helveg Petersen (Radical 
Liberal Party) yesterday after a meeting with Thai Foreign 
Minister Prasong Sunsiri in Bangkok. This means that Thailand 
will become the first developing country ever to cease to 
qualify for Danish aid because its economy is too well developed. 
  "But I have stressed that the country can receive other 
forms 
of aid. For example, soft loans and credits for noncommercial 
purposes," Helveg Petersen said. 
  Thailand will also be able to take $25 million from 
Denmark's 
environment and catastrophe fund as compensation for the loss of 
aid. [passage omitted] 
  During the talks the foreign minister also touched on 
Thailand's relations with neighboring Burma. 
  "I stressed that every opportunity must be taken to put 
pressure on the Burmese Government, and that I believe that 
Thailand must continue to grant residence permits to Burmese 
refugees," the foreign minister said. 

</TEXT>

