<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Denies Kantor To Visit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2001080894 Tokyo KYODO in English 0748 GMT 20 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2001080894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 20 KYODO -- Japan's vice trade minister 
on Thursday [20 January] denied reports that U.S. Trade 
Representative Mickey Kantor will visit Japan in an attempt to 
push stalled bilateral "framework" trade talks before the 
February Japan-U.S. summit. 
  Tokyo has not received such notification from the United 
States, Hideaki Kumano, vice international trade and industry 
minister, told a press conference. 
  Kumano said the reported visit by Kantor before the February 
11 meeting between Japanese Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa and 
U.S. President Bill Clinton would "not be realistic" in view of 
a tight political schedule in Japan up to the summit. 
  Kumano dismissed reported U.S. accusations that Japanese 
bureaucrats are helping foot-drag progress in bilateral trade 
talks. 
  Tokyo has not received specific U.S. requests to improve the 
situation, Kumano said, adding the government has responded 
appropriately by holding talks with the trade minister when 
necessary. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

