<H3> <TI>   Defense Chief Urges Readiness for Korean War </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2101090794 Tokyo KYODO in English 0850 GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2101090794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 21 KYODO -- Defense Agency Director 
General Kazuo Aichi said Friday [21 January] that Japan should 
prepare for the eventuality of war on the Korean peninsula, even 
though there is no immediate danger. 
  "Although the Korean peninsula has not become particularly 
strained, considering the fact that tension exists there we must 
study how to respond to various situations arising from a 
hypothetical outbreak of conflict," Aichi told reporters. 
  Aichi was believed to be alluding to possible economic 
sanctions imposed by the United Nations Security Council against 
North Korea over Pyongyang's suspected nuclear weapons program. 
  North Korea has warned that it will not stand idle if 
subjected to an economic blockade. 
  On the question of Japanese support for U.S. troops based in 
Japan were such a conflict to break out, Aichi said it would be 
decided on a "case-by-case" basis. 
  "We would have to consider to what extent we could (lend 
support) in the context of maintaining the Japan-U.S. alliance," 
he said. 
  Defense Agency officials said the United States has already 
asked for Japan's support in such an event. They said the 
request is being considered primarily by the Foreign Ministry. 

</TEXT>

