<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Political Reform Bills Approach Diet Vote </TI></H3>
<H4>   Panel Approves Package </H4>
<F P=102> OW2001023094 Tokyo KYODO in English 0223 GMT 20 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2001023094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 20 KYODO -- A government-proposed 
political reform package barely scraped through a vote in a 
House of Councillors panel Thursday [20 January] morning, paving 
the way for a showdown vote in the full chamber that could make 
or break Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa's five-month-old 
administration. 
  The upper chamber's Special Committee on Political Reform 
approved the package of four bills by a voice vote. 
  Eighteen committee members were in favor and 16 were 
against. 
  Hosokawa has staked his job on the passage of the political 
reform bills which call for members of the House of 
Representatives to be elected through a combination of 
single-seat constituencies and proportional representation, in 
place of the current multiseat constituencies. 
  Originally designed to clean up Japan's scandal-tainted 
political system, the package also calls for a limited 
tightening of curbs on political funds. 
  It remains unclear, however, whether the coalition can 
secure 
their passage by a full session of the upper chamber in view of 
dissent among some legislators of the Social Democratic Party, 
the biggest party in the ruling coalition. 
  The coalition, which hopes to have the vote by the full 
house 
on Friday, has a slim majority with a combined force of 131, 
compared with the opposition's 115. It needs 126 votes to be 
sure of winning. 
  The committee vote came after eleventh-hour talks Wednesday 
between the coalition and LDP [Liberal Democratic Party] failed 
to achieve a compromise over LDP demands to modify the bills. 
  The powerful lower chamber passed the package on November 
18. 

</TEXT>

