<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Political Reform Bills Approach Diet Vote </TI></H3>
<H4>   Hosokawa Ready To Talk to LDP </H4>
<F P=102> OW2001062494 Tokyo KYODO in English 0610 GMT 20 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2001062494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 20 KYODO -- Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa on Thursday [20 January] expressed readiness to talk 
with Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) President Yohei Kono to 
reconcile differences over LDP proposals on modifying the 
government's political reform package. 
  Fielding questions from reporters, the premier said that 
whether the meeting with Kono takes place is entirely up to the 
LDP. 
  "If the LDP wants to hold the summit, I am ready to respond 
immediately," said Hosokawa, in an upbeat mood following the 
passage of the package through a House of Councillors committee 
earlier in the day. The vote was 18 for and 16 against. 
  The package is designed to redesign the mechanism for 
electing members of the House of Representatives of the 
two-chamber diet, while changing the political fund-raising 
system by channeling donations to politicians through their 
parties' coffers. 
  Kono, meanwhile, ruled out holding a meeting with Hosokawa 
on 
possible modifications of the package. 
  He told reporters at the LDP headquarters, "at present, 
there 
remains no room for us to advance suggestions" to the coalition 
side. 
  On Wednesday, negotiators from the coalition and LDP failed 
to narrow a gap over the LDP's three demands, including the one 
calling for raising from 274 to 280 the number of lower house 
seats to be contested as single-seat constituencies in a 
500-seat chamber. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

