<DOCNO> FBIS3-47947 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas014_a_94018" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-014 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  21 January 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Political Reform Bills Approach Diet Vote </TI></H3>
<H4>   Vote Outcome `Uncertain' </H4>
<F P=102> OW2101054394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0532 GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2101054394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 21 KYODO -- The outcome of a vote by 
the plenary session of the House of Councillors on Prime 
Minister Morihiro Hosokawa's reform bills remains uncertain with 
the meeting due to start at 3 p.m. [0600 GMT] Friday [21 
January]. 
  Leaders of both ruling coalition parties and the opposition 
Liberal Democratic Party were continuing their efforts to 
persuade rebel members within their camps to vote in line with 
their parties' policies. 
  Hosokawa has reiterated his resolve to stake his political 
future on the package of four bills designed to introduce a 
combination of single-seat constituencies and proportional 
representation in the House of Representatives. 
  Failure to pass the bills could lead to Hosokawa's 
resignation or dissolution of the lower house for a general 
election, many political analysts said. 
  If enacted, the package could consolidate the political 
power 
base of Hosokawa, whose seven-party coalition government broke 
the LDP's 38-year grip on power last August, and trigger further 
realignments in the country's political arena, they said. 
  The seven coalition parties have a total of 131 seats in the 
252-member upper chamber while the opposition LDP, the Japanese 
Communist Party and Niin Club have 115. A simple majority of 
the full house is 126. 
  More than 10 upper house members of the Social Democratic 
Party (SDP), the largest force in the coalition government, 
however, have expressed opposition to the package, fearing the 
introduction of single-seat electoral districts in the lower 
house might deal a severe blow to the party. 
  Some LDP members are also expected to defy the party 
leadership and vote for the bills. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

