<H3> <TI>   Reaction to Rejection of Political Reform Bills </TI></H3>
<H4>   Hosokawa To Pursue Passage </H4>
<F P=102> OW2101094894 Tokyo KYODO in English 0938 GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2101094894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 21 KYODO -- Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa said Friday [21 January] he will pursue to the very end 
of the current Diet session on January 29 enactment of the 
political reform bills rejected by the upper house earlier in 
the day. 
  At a press conference following the rejection of the 
government-sponsored package of four bills by the House of 
Councillors, Hosokawa said he will do his utmost during the 
remaining days of the Diet session to have the package passed. 
  Hosokawa said he has no plans to dissolve the House of 
Representative for a snap general election or resign over his 
failure to have the bills clear the Diet. 
  The premier has repeatedly suggested he would step down or 
dissolve the lower house if he failed to get the political 
reform bills enacted. 
  Hosokawa said he will seek the enactment of the reform bills 
through a joint meeting of representatives from both chambers. 
  Under Article 59 of the Constitution, the lower house can 
call such a joint meeting to reach a compromise on bills 
rejected by the upper house. 
  The 252-member upper chamber voted down the bills aimed at 
introducing a election system combining single-seat 
constituencies and proportional representation in the lower 
house and changing the system of political fund-raising. The 
bills cleared the lower house on November 18. 
  A total of 17 upper house members of the Social Democratic 
Party [of Japan], the largest force in the coalition government, 
voted against the bills in defiance of the party line. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

