<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reaction to Rejection of Political Reform Bills </TI></H3>
<H4>   SDPJ Respnsibility Called `Grave' </H4>
<F P=102> OW2101101594 Tokyo KYODO in English 0953 GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2101101594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 21 KYODO -- The leadership of the Social 
Democratic Party [of Japan] (SDP) [SDPJ], the largest group in 
the coalition government, will likely come under pressure to 
resign after failing to unite its members in passing 
government-proposed political reform bills through the Diet, 
political sources said Friday [21 January]. 
  SDP Chairman Tomiichi Murayama told a meeting of the party's 
legislators that "the party's responsibility is grave." 
  But Murayama did not specify if he will take responsibility 
for the failure by resigning as chairman of the largest force 
within the seven-party coalition government. 
  In a plenary session Friday afternoon, the House of 
Councillors voted down the package of four political reform 
bills with a vote of 130-118. 
  Although the seven coalition parties hold a majority in the 
252-seat upper house, 17 SDP members voted with the opposition 
to defeat the bills. 
  After the voting, Koken Nosaka, chairman of the SDP's Diet 
Affairs Committee, told reporters the failure of the bills "will 
be the responsibility of the (SDP's) leadership." 
  The SDP is expected to expel the 17 members who voted 
against 
the bills from the party, party sources said. 
  Murayama said Thursday he might resign if an expected 
rebellion by several SDP legislators led to the breakdown of the 
reform package in Friday's vote. 
  "If the political reform package fails to clear the upper 
chamber as a result of SDP legislators' opposition, I will take 
responsibility as the SDP chairman, as our party would not be 
able to disclaim resultant political responsibility," he said. 

</TEXT>

