<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reaction to Rejection of Political Reform Bills </TI></H3>
<H4>   Business Leaders Regret Vote </H4>
<F P=102> OW2101114294 Tokyo KYODO in English 1038 GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2101114294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 21 Kyodo -- Japanese business leaders 
expressed regret over the House of Councillors' rejection Friday 
[21 January] of the coalition government's political reform 
package. 
  Gaishi Hiraiwa, chairman of the Federation of Economic 
Organizations (Keidanren), said it was "highly regrettable" that 
the four political reform bills were killed. 
  Kosaku Inaba, chairman of the Japan Chamber of Commerce and 
Industry, called the failure a dark day for Japan and one that 
could further dampen the slumping economy. 
  Inaba also expressed concern that the setback for political 
reform could slow economic deregulation that had been promoted 
by Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa's administration. 
  Masaru Hayami, chairman of the Japan Association of 
Corporate 
Executives (Keizai Doyukai), said a joint committee of both 
chambers of the Diet should compromise so that the package is 
enacted. 
  Takeshi Nagano, president of the Federation of Employers 
Associations (Nikkeiren), said failure to enact the package 
could heighten public distrust of politics and damage Japan's 
image overseas. 

</TEXT>

