<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chamber of Commerce Head Urges Income Tax Cut </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2001100394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0902 GMT 20 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2001100394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 20 KYODO -- The Commerce Chamber head 
on Thursday [20 January] urged the government to carry out an 
income tax reduction of 7 trillion yen in order to revive the 
ailing Japanese economy. 
  A substantially large-scale income tax cut is necessary in 
light of the delay in implementing a tax reduction, Kosaku 
Inaba, chairman of the Japan Chamber of Commerce and Industry, 
told a press conference. 
  Inaba also said the government should begin studying a 
consumption tax hike as a means of covering the income tax cut, 
after confirming the economy has turn around. 
  Inaba said the ruling coalition parties and the opposition 
camp should do their utmost to avoid creating a political vacuum 
over the issue of political reforms. 
  The most urgent task facing the government is the formation 
of a third supplementary budget for fiscal 1993 and the main 
budget for fiscal 1994, he said. 

</TEXT>

