<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Keidanren Head Urges Effective Economic Stimulus </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1901111894 Tokyo KYODO in English 1029 GMT 19 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1901111894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokushima, Jan. 19 KYODO -- Gaishi Hiraiwa, head of 
the powerful Federation of Economic Organizations (Keidanren), 
urged the government Wednesday [19 January] to implement 
effective pump-priming measures as soon as possible. 
  The Keidanren expects the government to take measures 
without 
interruption, said Hiraiwa, who visited this western Japan city 
to attend a meeting of regional business leaders. 
  No effective economy stimulus measures have been taken since 
Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa took office last August, he 
said. 
  He urged the government to reduce corporate taxes along with 
income tax cuts in view of flagging corporate expenditures. 
  Hiraiwa said it is inappropriate to discuss employment 
security and wage hikes as a matter of option. 
  Both are important problems and the Keidanren will continue 
to make efforts to realize both, he said. 
  Hiroshi Saito, vice chairman of the federation and chairman 
of the world's leading steel maker Nippon Steel Corp., who was 
present at the meeting, called for income tax cuts at least two 
years ahead of a consumption tax hike. 
  He proposed the floating of national bonds to secure funds 
for the tax cuts. 
  It is confusing to talk about pump-priming measures and a 
revision of the tax system in the long run at the same time, he 
said. 

</TEXT>

