<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cable System Favored for Broadcasting Service </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1701133794 Tokyo KYODO in English 1237 GMT 17 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1701133794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 17 KYODO -- A majority of corporate 
executives and heads of local entities favor cable transmission 
for broadcasting in the 21st century when an optical fiber 
telecommunications system is completed, the Postal Ministry said 
Monday [17 January]. 
  The Posts and Telecommunications Ministry said the survey 
also showed that those polled called for allocation of radio 
frequencies for mobile telecommunications networks. 
  The ministry said the report was based on interviews with 
372 
heads of local governments and corporate executives, as well as 
academics, from last October to the year-end. 
  About 90 percent of the pollees called for emphasis to be 
placed on the consolidation of telecommunications networks in 
developing the social infrastructure in the 21st century, the 
ministry said. 
  A majority of the pollees called for cable transmission to 
be 
set aside for broadcasting, while allotting radio frequencies to 
the mobile telecommunications network, the ministry said. 
  The results of the survey were reported to the 
Telecommunications Council, an advisory organ in the ministry. 

</TEXT>

