<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sanyo To Boost Output of Optical Pickups </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1701010894 Tokyo KYODO in English 0020 GMT 17 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1701010894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Osaka, Jan. 17 KYODO -- Sanyo Electric Co. said 
Monday [17 January] it will boost production of optical pickups, 
a key component for compact disc (CD) players, to meet rapidly 
rising demand. 
  Optical pickups are used to read digital signals for optical 
disks. 
  The Osaka-based consumer electronics company will raise 
overall production in Japan and overseas for its business year 
ending in November to 24.9 million pickups. 
  Optical pickups are in strong demand due to wider use of 
minidiscs and compact disc read-only memories (CD-ROMs). 
  Sanyo is churning out the high value-added electronic 
component in Japan, China and South Korea, with combined output 
coming to 14.7 million in the year which ended last November. 
  Currently, the company holds a 25 percent share in the 
global 
market, in which Sony Corp. commands the lion's share of about 
60 percent, according to industry analysts. 
  They say total sales are expected to gain 20 percent to 72 
million pickups in the world marketplace. 

</TEXT>

