<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Top 30 Business Groups Select Prime Companies </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1901032694 Seoul THE KOREA TIMES in English 19 Jan 94 p 8 </F>
<F P=103> SK1901032694 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul THE KOREA TIMES </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The nation's top 30 business groups have selected 
their prime industries and companies which they will nurture as 
world-top enterprises in order to enhance their international 
competitiveness. 
  They submitted the lists of their choices to the Ministry of 
Trade, Industry and Energy yesterday, the government-set 
deadline. 
  The selection of core industrial sectors and companies by 
the 
30 largest conglomerates, which was conceived by the government 
last July, is aimed at business "specialization" as a means to 
strengthen the competitiveness of Korean products in 
international markets. 
  As permitted in the guideline, the top 10 of the 30 groups 
except for Kia chose three prime industries each, while Kia and 
the remaining 20 selected two core industries each. 
  The top 10 are Hyundai, Samsung, Daewoo, Lucky-Goldstar, 
Sunkyong, Hanjin, Ssangyong, Kia, Hanhwa and Lotte. 
  Specifically, Hyundai decided on electronics, automobiles 
and 
energy; Samsung electronics, machinery and petrochemicals; 
Daewoo machinery, automobiles and distribution; Lucky-Goldstar 
electronics, petrochemicals and energy, and Sunkyong energy, 
petrochemicals and distribution. 
  Hanjin chose machinery, distribution and construction; 
Ssangyong energy, non-metals and automobiles; Kia automobiles 
and steel; Hanhwa energy, petrochemicals and distribution, and 
Lotte food &amp; beverages, petrochemicals and distribution. 
  The 20 other groups are Kumho, Daelim, Doosan, Dong-Ah, 
Hanjin, Hyosung, Dongkuk Steel, Sammi, Halla, Tongyang, Kolon, 
Jinro, Dongbu, Kohap, Kukdong, Woosung, Haitai, Byucksan, Miwon 
and Samyang. 
  Kumho selected petrochemicals and distribution; Daelim 
construction and non-metals; Doosan food &amp; beverages and 
construction; Dong-Ah construction and distribution; Hanil 
textiles, and construction; Hyosung petrochemicals and 
electronics, Dongkuk Steel distribution and steel; Sammi 
distribution and steel; Halla automobiles and machinery, and 
Tongyang electronics and distribution. 
  Kolon picked petrochemicals and distribution; Jinro food 
&amp; 
beverages and distribution; Dongbu steel and distribution; Kohap 
petrochemicals and distribution; Kukdong construction and non- 
metals; Woosung construction and distribution; Haitai food &amp; 
beverages and distribution; Byucksan non-metals and 
construction; Miwon food &amp; beverages and petrochemicals, and 
Samyang food &amp; beverages and petrochemicals. 
  The 30 top business groups were implicitly permitted to pick 
one or two core companies in each selected prime industrial line 
although there is no regulation on that matter in the guideline. 
  Of the 10 largest conglomerates, Hyundai picked five 
including Hyundai Electronics and Hyundai Motor; Samsung five 
including Samsung Electronics and Samsung General Chemicals; 
Daewoo four including Daewoo Shipbuilding &amp; Heavy Machinery 
and 
Daewoo Motor; Lucky-Goldstar six including Goldstar and Lucky, 
and Sunkyong six including Yukong and Sunkyong. 
  Selected core industrial lines will be free of the 
government's strict control on borrowing fresh bank loans by the 
top 30 business groups. 


