<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Views IAEA Negotiations </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2101044094 Pyongyang KCNA in English 0430 GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2101044094 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, January 21 (KCNA) -- A spokesman for the 
Foreign Ministry of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea 
answered a question put by KCNA today regarding the on-going 
negotiations between the DPRK and the International Atomic 
Energy Agency [IAEA] in Vienna. 
  Negotiations on the continuity of safeguards are now going 
on 
between an official of the DPRK Embassy in Austria and an 
official of the Secretariat of the IAEA. 
  The negotiations were arranged according to an agreement 
between the DPRK and the United States. 
  As already reported, at the DPRK-U.S. contact held in New 
York toward the end of last year, the U.S. side officially 
manifested its will to suspend the Team Spirit joint military 
maneuvers, a test nuclear war, as part of the measures for 
removing nuclear threat to the DPRK, and we decided to accept 
inspection for the continuity of safeguards in conformity with 
our special position after the temporary suspension of the 
effectuation of our withdrawal from the Non-Proliferation Treaty 
[NPT]. 
  What we decided to allow is not routine or ad hoc inspection 
pursuant to the obligation under the NPT, but inspection merely 
for the continuity of safeguards conforming to our special 
position. 
  We proposed a scope of inspection enough to guarantee the 
continuity of safeguards at the current negotiations with the 
IAEA. 
  The IAEA should show an affirmative response to defining the 
scope of inspection commensurate with the guarantee of the 
continuity of safeguards at the negotiations, as agreed between 
the DPRK and the USA. 
  As we have already declared, the issue of routine and ad hoc 
inspection under the safeguards agreement shall be resolved 
smoothly, if the third round of the DPRK-USA talks are held and 
an agreement is reached on the package solution. 
  Therefore, there will be no ground for the IAEA Secretariat 
to refuse to respond to our reasonable proposal, if it is 
interested in the solution of the nuclear issue and the 
guarantee of the continuity of safeguards on the Korean 
peninsula. 
  We make it clear that, if the continuity of the safeguards 
fails to be guaranteed due to the absurd assertion of the IAEA 
Secretariat, we cannot be held responsible for it and the 
responsibility lies with the opposite side which complicated the 
nuclear issue on the Korean peninsula. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-48013 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas014_m_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-014 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  21 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

