<F P=101> Brunei, Malaysia &amp; Singapore </F>
<H3> <TI>   Former Sabah Official, ISA Detainee Released </TI></H3>
<H4>   Mahathir Not To Appoint New Minister </H4>
<F P=102> BK2001145194 Kuala Lumpur Radio Malaysia Network in Malay 
1300 GMT 20 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2001145194 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuala Lumpur Radio Malaysia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Malay </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Datuk Sri Dr. Mahathir says the government has 
no plans to appoint a new Sabah affairs minister to replace Tun 
Datu Mustapha, who resigned yesterday. The resignation of Tun 
Datu Mustapha as Sabah affairs minister, chairman of the UMNO 
[United Malays National Organization] Merudu Division, and 
consequently an UMNO member will not affect anyone. Tun Datu 
Mustapha had the right to make this decision. It showed, 
however, that Tun Datu Mustapaha was not committed to UMNO. 
[passage omitted] 
  Asked about Datuk Jeffrey Kitingan, director of the Sabah 
Foundation, who has cited the possibility of playing politics to 
revamp relations between the federal government and the Sabah 
Government, Datuk Sri Dr. Mahathir said that the federal 
government has never quarreled with the people of Sabah. The 
federal government merely disagrees with the present Sabah 
leadership: 
  [Begin Mahathir recording] I have heard these rumors for a 
long time. Indeed, they want to be readmitted into the National 
Front. We cannot just readmit them, though. You remember that 
we admitted them after they insisted, but they quit the National 
Front easily at a time when we were facing a general election. 
Thus, we cannot readmit them easily. First, we want to know 
the extent and see the proof of their commitment. If they are 
able to prove that they really had nothing to do with their 
leader's action, we will consider readmitting them, because we 
are not extremely rigid; we have mercy for them. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

