<F P=101> Brunei, Malaysia &amp; Singapore </F>
<H3> <TI>   Former Sabah Official, ISA Detainee Released </TI></H3>
<H4>   Unconditional Release </H4>
<F P=102> BK2101104194 Kuala Lumpur NEW STRAITS TIMES in English 20 
Jan 94 p 1 </F>

<F P=103> BK2101104194 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuala Lumpur NEW STRAITS TIMES </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Azran Aziz and Kamarul Zaman Salleh] </F>
  [Excerpts] Seremban, Wed -- Former Sabah Foundation 
director Datuk Dr. Jeffrey Kitingan was today released without 
any conditions from restricted residence under the Internal 
Security Act [ISA]. 
  This was confirmed by Negri Sembilan police chief SAC 
[Senior 
Assistant Commissioner] 1 Abas Johar here. 
  Kitingan was released from the Kamunting detention camp on 
December 22 last year after being held there under the Internal 
Security Act since May 13,1991, and put under restricted 
residence in Seremban for a duration of not more than two years. 
Under the earlier restriction order, Kitingan was not allowed 
to write or help to write any article that is political in 
nature, hold gatherings in his house or compound or in any 
building under his control or make Press statements. 
  Kitingan, 45, collected his release letter after police 
officers escorted him from the Allson Klana Resort hotel to the 
police headquarters at 12.25pm [0425 GMT]. 
  He said he was very happy and thanked Prime Minister Datuk 
Sri Dr. Mahathir Mohamed, who is also Home Minister, for 
releasing him unconditionally. 
  "I am very happy and I take this opportunity to thank Dr. 
Mahathir for releasing me without any conditions," he told 
reporters at the hotel lobby. 
  Kitingan said he hoped the Prime Minister would also release 
other Sabah people who were still under restricted residence. 
  He said he would leave for Sabah tomorrow morning. 
  Asked if he would contest a seat in the forthcoming Sabah 
State elections, he said, he would do so if he was named as a 
candidate. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

