<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Conference on Bosnia Held in Kuala Lumpur </TI></H3>
<H4>   Bosnian President Speaks 22 Jan </H4>
<F P=102> BK2201105194 Kuala Lumpur BERNAMA in English 0746 GMT 22 Jan 
94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2201105194 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuala Lumpur BERNAMA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kuala Lumpur, Jan. 22 (OANA-BERNAMA) -- Bosnian 
President Alija Izetbegovic Saturday called on the international 
community to implement the more than 30 resolutions adopted by 
the United Nations to end Serb atrocities against Bosnians in 
the former Yugoslav republic. He said so far only one 
resolution -- the arms embargo against Bosnia-Herzegovina -- had 
been enforced. 
  This resolution is against the interest of Bosnians as they 
are unable to defend themselves from the Serb atrocities, he 
told the international conference of parliamentarians on 
Bosnia-Herzegovina here. 
  The two-day conference attended by about 180 
parliamentarians 
from more than 30 countries was opened by Malaysian Prime 
Minister Dr. Mahathir Mohamed. 
  Referring to Article 51 of the UN Charter which says that an 
independent state under atteck had every right to defend itself, 
Izetbegovic called on the UN to lift the embargo. 
  He said his people were not seeking an ideological state of 
any kind but only wanted to preserve a democratic secular state. 
  He dismissed the misconception that the war in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina was either a civil war or religious war. 
  It is actually genocide... It's the war against every 
religion, he said. 
  Izetbegovic said the war could not be stopped through 
appeals 
or resolutions. The aggressors don't understand this type of 
logic. We have to confront force with force, he added. 
  After the failure of the recent peace negotiations in 
Geneva, 
we (the Bosnian Muslims) have been accused of rejecting calls 
for peace in Bosnia-Herzegovina. We don't reject peace, he said. 
  He added that the division of Bosnia-Herzegovina into three 
mini-ethnic states was meant to confine Bosnian Muslims and 
deprive them of access to the sea. 
  Izetbegovic said children and adults, young and old, were 
being murdered and driven from their homes, while the women 
faced constant rape in bosnia where concentration camps just 
like those during World War II have reemerged. 
  He expressed appreciation to Dr. Mahathir and the Malaysian 
people for their continued support to seek and ensure justice 
and fairness for the Bosnians. 
  He said Malaysia's multicultural and multireligious 
population was similar to that of his country. 
  Malaysia has proven that there can be tolerance in such a 
society, he added. 
  Izetbegovic hoped the conference would pave the way for an 
international campaign against Serb atrocities in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

