<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Conference on Bosnia Held in Kuala Lumpur </TI></H3>
<H4>   Conference Calls for New Peace Talks </H4>
<F P=102> BK2301144694 Kuala Lumpur Radio Malaysia Network in Malay 
1300 GMT 23 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2301144694 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuala Lumpur Radio Malaysia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Malay </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The international conference of parliamentarians on 
Bosnia-Herzegovina ended in Kuala Lumpur today with a call for 
the convening of a new international conference to replace the 
Geneva peace talks. All parliamentarians from 33 countries who 
attended the two-day conference vowed to wage a campaign for a 
new conference. 
  A resolution issued at the end of the conference today 
called 
on all countries to support an initiative to lift the ban on 
arms exports to Bosnia-Herzegovina. The parliamentarians also 
voiced their reservations against the Bosnia peace negotiators, 
who had acted against the UN Charter and the London Conference. 
They also called on the United Nations to take immediate action 
to save Sarajevo and other cities from Serbian destruction. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-48056 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas015aa_94006" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-015 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  24 January 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Conference on Bosnia Held in Kuala Lumpur </TI></H3>
<H4>   Bosnian President on Peace Talks </H4>
<F P=102> BK2401072494 Kuala Lumpur BERNAMA in English 0707 GMT 24 Jan 
94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2401072494 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuala Lumpur BERNAMA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kuala Lumpur, Jan. 24 (OANA-BERNAMA) -- Malaysia's 
proposal to convene a new international conference to solve the 
conflict in Bosnia-Herzegovina has received the support of 
Bosnian President Alija Izetbegovic. 
  Izetbegovic said: We believe that convening a new 
international conference on Bosnia-Herzegovina on a larger basis 
and including a larger number of participants would be useful, 
especially if it will reaffirm the principles passed at the 
London (peace) conference last year. 
  It was obvious that the last round of talks convened in 
Geneva a few days ago had exhausted all possibilities, he told a 
press conference here Monday to mark the end of his four-day 
working visit to Malaysia. 
  Earlier, Izetbegovic held a four-eyed meeting with Deputy 
Prime Minister Datuk Sri Anwar Ibrahim. The meeting lasted for 
an hour. 
  The idea to convene the new peace conference was mooted by 
Prime Minister Dr. Mahathir Mohamed in his address when opening 
the two-day international conference of parliamentarians on 
Bosnia-Herzegovina on Saturday. 
  The 10 parliamentarians from more than 30 countries, who 
attended the international conference of parliamentarians on 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, also called for fresh peace initiatives, 
including the convening of a new international conference, 
citing the non-accountability of the present mediators in the 
on-going peace negotiations to the United Nations. 
  Asked if the other two warring factions -- Serbs and Croats 
-- would agree to such a conference, Izetbegovic said: I cannot 
be sure about the attitude of the other sides. 
  He reiterated, however, that the conflict and violence in 
the 
former Yugoslav republic could not be solved through resolutions 
and appeals. 
  There is no case in history in which any violence and force 
was stopped by resolutions or an appeal no matter how good the 
resolution was, he said through his daughter, Sabina, who acted 
as interpreter. 
  Izetbegovic said he would attend the next round of peace 
talks in Geneva scheduled for Feb. 10. 

</TEXT>

