<F P=100> Cambodia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministers Meet Visiting Austrian </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK2201152594 Phnom Penh National Voice of Cambodia Radio 
Network in Cambodian 1300 GMT 22 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2201152594 </F>
<F P=104>  Phnom Penh National Voice of Cambodia Radio 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Cambodian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] This afternoon His Excellency [H.E.] Ing Kiet, state 
minister and minister of public works and transport; and H.E. Pu 
Sothirak, minister of industry, mines, and energy, together 
received H.E. Wolfgang Schallenberg, Austrian deputy foreign 
minister. The talks concerned the plan to repair the Kirirom 
hydropower network. 
  H.E. Austrian Deputy Foreign Minister said that a plan to 
restore the Kirirom hydropower network, worth about $11 million, 
will be signed between Austria and Cambodia in the near future. 
Austria will dispatch technicians to carry out this plan. The 
Kirirom hydropwer station was built in 1965 by the former 
Yugoslavia and was operational in 1968. This station provided 
up to 10,000 kilowatts of power during the rainy season and 
about 5,000 kilowatt in the dry season. Many parts, however, 
have been damaged since 1970 when the hydropower station was 
abandoned. 
  Austria and Sweden have been authorized by the Royal 
Government of Cambodia to study the plan to restore this 
hydropower network. Austria plans to provide about $11 million 
for the project and another $46,000 for protection and mine 
clearing in the Kirirom area. 

</TEXT>

