<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Indian Paper Urges Settling `Comfort Women' Issue </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1801151694 Pyongyang KCNA in English 1502 GMT 18 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1801151694 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, January 18 (KCNA) -- THE INDIAN TIMES 
January [word indistinct] urged the Japanese Government to 
properly solve the "comfort women" problem. 
  The paper said the problem is liable to "charges of the 
violation of human morality" under international law. 
  The atrocities of the Japanese imperialists in reducing 
nearly 200,000 innocent Korean women in their teens and twenties 
to sexual slaves for the "imperial Army" and violating them and 
brutally [word indistinct] them were the most heinous crimes 
without precedent, said the paper. 
  The "comfort women" issue can by no means be buried in 
oblivion by a "humanitarian relief fund" or by a political 
tieup, it noted. 
  The main point in the solution of the issue is for Japan to 
make an overall investigation into the truth of the crimes, make 
public its results and make an honest apology and adequate 
compensation, the paper stressed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

