<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   KCNA Describes Countries' `Communist Morality' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1701104694 Pyongyang KCNA in English 1021 GMT 17 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1701104694 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Korea Pervaded With Feelings of Kinship" -- KCNA headline] </F>
  [Text] Pyongyang, January 17 (KCNA) -- A beautiful 
communist morality has come into full bloom in Korea where many 
people have brought home and taken good care of orphaned 
children and old folks with no one to rely upon like their real 
parents and real sons and daughters. 
  Last year, An Kwang-nam, a worker of the Kangso District 
coal 
mining complex, Chong Myong-il, a worker of the Uiju County 
urban management office in North Pyongan Province, and many 
other people adopted orphaned children and brought home lonely 
old men and women and took utmost care of them. 
  The great leader President Kim Il-song, long ago, put 
forward 
the slogan "One for all and all for one!" and has made sure that 
a beautiful communist morality of helping and leading each other 
forward pervades the whole country. 
  At the national meeting of mothers held in November 1961 he 
highly estimated Yi Yong-suk, a woman in Sunchon City, South 
Pyongan Province, who adopted and brought up nine war orphans 
during the fatherland liberation war, saying her example should 
be generalized throughout the country, and saw to it that the 
title of labour heroine was awarded to her. 
  Kim Hui-chong, a labour heroine living in Taetan County, 
South Hwanghae Province, brought up 15 children of fallen 
fighters to be reliable officials of the country. 
  Kim Yun-yong, principal of the Pyongyang Sangdang Primary 
School, Yi Hwa-yong, secretary of the primary party committee of 
the welfare cooperative in Waudo District, Nampo municipality, 
Wi Hwak-sil, a resident in Kumchon County, North Hwanghae 
Province, Hwang Pi-pong, a worker of the Nahung washing machine 
factory in Iwon County, South Hamgyong Province, and many others 
also became parents of orphaned children and brought home and 
look after old men and women with no one to support them. 
  The dear leader Comrade Kim Chong-il highly estimated their 
deeds and sent benevolent gifts to them. Last year, he praised 
as a very good party worker and extended thanks to Chang 
Sa-hong, secretary of the primary party committee of an organ 
under the General Bureau of Western Railways, who had taken warm 
care of the son and daughter of a worker who died, giving more 
thought to them than to his own children. 
  Indeed, there is not a single orphan, not a single lonely 
old 
person in the Democratic People's Republic of Korea where the 
leader, the party and the masses are united in one mind and the 
entire people form one big family. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-48109 </DOCNO>
