<H3> <TI>   Reportage on U.S. Treasury Secretary's Visit </TI></H3>
<H4>   Hata, Saito on Bentsen Remarks </H4>
<F P=102> OW2401100694 Tokyo KYODO in English 1000 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2401100694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 24 KYODO -- The Japanese Government on 
Monday [24 January] described as "untimely" remarks by U.S. 
Treasury Secretary Lloyd Bentsen over the weekend that 
Washington may "reexamine" the bilateral trade framework talks 
if no accord is reached before a Japan-U.S. summit on February 
11. Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata told a press conference that 
Bentsen made the remarks "too early" since vice 
ministerial-level talks are now under way in Washington. 
  At a separate news conference, Vice Foreign Minister 
Kunihiko 
Saito also called Bentsen's remarks "untimely" and "not 
constructive" because both sides are engaging in serious 
discussions to achieve agreements. Saito said it was not timely 
because Japan and the U.S. have been strengthening their 
efforts to produce such accords. 
  On Sunday, Bentsen said the United States "will not settle 
for any cosmetic agreement" on trade and that "if we do not have 
credible agreements by the time of the summit, we would have to 
reexamine the basis of the framework." Bentsen said his remarks 
are not meant as a threat but were "just the logical 
consequence," reflecting "the realities of the situation." 

</TEXT>

