<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government: U.S. Investment Talks `Preliminary' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2201013494 Tokyo KYODO in English 0126 GMT 22 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2201013494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Washington, Jan. 21 KYODO -- Japan and the United 
States wrapped up three days of working-level trade talks Friday 
[21 January] to address issues of foreign direct investment in 
both countries, Japanese officials said. The "working group" 
session on investment is part of the wide-ranging framework 
trade talks the two countries have been holding to increase 
access and sales of foreign goods and services in Japan. 
  Officials from the two countries were also meeting 
separately 
in Washington on the access and sales of auto parts in Japan. 
  Japanese officials characterized the latest session on 
investment issues as preliminary, noting that the investment 
sector is not on the "priority list" that must be completed by 
the February 11 summit between Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa 
and President Bill Clinton. 
  Discussions were limited primarily to a presentation of 
matters of concern both to the U.S. and Japan on investment 
issues. Among the issues the U.S. raised were excessive 
government regulation on foreign direct investment and problems 
foreign investors face in the acquisition of Japanese 
corporations. 
  Washington has charged that Japan deliberately blocks the 
entry of foreign capital into Japan, which U.S. officials said 
has caused a "substantial loss of potential exports" from 
foreign firms to their Japanese subsidiaries. 
  According to U.S. figures, Japan hosted about 12 billion 
dollars in foreign direct investment in 1991, representing only 
0.7 percent of the world's stock of inward direct investment. 
  By contrast, the U.S. hosted 414 billion dollars, or 22 
percent, of the stock of inward direct investment. The 
corresponding figure for the European Union -- as the former 
European Community is now known -- was 714 billion dollars, or 
38 percent, U.S. officials said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-48119 </DOCNO>
