<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hata: Russian Aid Policy Remains Unchanged </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2401111094 Tokyo KYODO in English 1051 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2401111094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 24 KYODO -- Japan's policy on aid to 
Russia remains unchanged despite the recent political 
instability there, Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata said Monday [24 
January]. At a press conference, Hata brushed aside some 
reports suggesting that Japan's policy on aid to Russia has 
changed because of recent political developments in Moscow, such 
as the resignations of reformers First Deputy Premier Yegor 
Gaydar and Finance Minister Boris Fedorov. 
  Japan's position to support, in cooperation with the Group 
of 
Seven (G-7) nations, Russia's efforts for democratization, a 
shift toward a market-oriented economy and a transition to a 
diplomacy based on law and justice, remains unchanged, Hata 
said. Japan is watching closely Russia's moves to form a 
cabinet and other developments concerning its domestic politics, 
but it has not yet changed its policy on aid to Russia, he said. 
  He said Tokyo will continue to extend the aid by grasping 
the 
progress of reforms in Russia and by understanding the needs of 
the Russian people. 
  Hata also said Russia's development and stabilization are 
important because the country has influence within the 
international community and great resources and technology. 

</TEXT>

