<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   More Reaction to Political Reform Bill Rejection </TI></H3>
<H4>   U.S. Reaction to `Setback' Noted </H4>
<F P=102> OW2101232494 Tokyo KYODO in English 2309 GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2101232494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Washington, Jan. 21 KYODO -- The defeat of Prime 
Minister Morihiro Hosokawa's political reform package at the 
hands of the House of Councillors Friday [21 January] sent shock 
waves among U.S. officials involved in crucial trade talks with 
Japan. "We're looking at the situation in Japan closely," U.S. 
Trade Representative Mickey Kantor said. "Obviously it's a 
fluid situation in which no one is quite sure what the outcome 
will be." 
  Bowman Cutter, deputy presidential assistant for economic 
policy and the White House point man coordinating the 
"framework" trade negotiations was more brunt. 
  The upper house's rejection of Hosokawa's initiative to 
overhaul the Japanese electoral system is a "significant 
setback" for the Japanese Government, cutter said in an 
interview on CNBC cable television. 
  Hosokawa's political troubles came as senior officials from 
the two countries were gearing up for a final round of trade 
talks ahead of a summit meeting in Washington with President 
Bill Clinton on February 11. 
  Deputy U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshevsky said 
the 
trade talks would proceed as scheduled. Like Kantor, she 
declined to comment on whether Hosokawa's political troubles 
would cloud prospects of the summit meeting. 
  Some U.S. political analysts were less circumspect. 
  "The political situation in Japan has become very dicey," 
said Douglas Paal, former special assistant for Asian affairs on 
the National Security Council. Paal told a private forum on 
U.S.-Japan trade relations that he believes the political 
upheavals in Tokyo will have "a big impact" on the 
Hosokawa-Clinton summit. 
  In his television interview, Cutter said Clinton remains 
"extremely supportive" of Hosokawa's reform efforts. 
  Senior U.S. Administration officials have said Washington 
had 
hoped Hosokawa would shift his focus to reviving the stalled 
Japanese economy once the political reform issue was out of the 
way. Cutter said Friday that Clinton still expects the Japanese 
Government to introduce a stimulus package, noting that the 
issues of political reform and economic stimulus are "quite 
distinct." 
  U.S. Treasury Secretary Lloyd Bentsen is due in Tokyo on 
Sunday for talks with Hosokawa and Finance Minister Hirohisa 
Fujii. 
  Tokyo and Washington are currently engaged in wide-ranging 
trade talks through which Washington hopes to secure a Japanese 
commitment to adopt specific measures to reduce its vast trade 
surplus and open up specific market sectors of particular 
interest to U.S. businesses. 
  The Clinton administration has repeatedly said the size of 
Japan's trade surplus is "politically untenable." Clinton 
himself reinforced his determination to cut the trade gap with 
Japan, saying on a television talk show Thursday that Japan is 
one of the "biggest problems" for U.S. trade. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-48126 </DOCNO>
