<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   More Reaction to Political Reform Bill Rejection </TI></H3>
<H4>   SDPJ Opposes Reviving Bills </H4>
<F P=102> OW2201120994 Tokyo KYODO in English 1157 GMT 22 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2201120994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 22 KYODO -- Leaders of the Social 
Democratic Party (SDP), the biggest group among seven parties in 
the ruling coalition, agreed Saturday [22 January] to oppose 
reviving reform bills sponsored by the Liberal Democratic Party 
(LDP) in an effort to reach a compromise, party officials said. 
The officials said top party executives and the party's central 
executive committee met and agreed that the SDP will continue to 
support a package of four government-proposed bills, which fell 
through in the House of Councillors on Friday. 
  The LDP bills allow corporations to give donations to 
individual politicians, while the government bills ban such 
donations and allow only corporate donations to political 
parties. 
  On Friday, Komeito Secretary General Yuichi Ichikawa hinted 
at accepting the LDP package as a compromise to enact political 
reform before the current extraordinary session of the Diet 
expires January 29. But the SDP strongly opposes easing 
proposed controls on political funding. 
  The SDP also decided to severely punish the 17 SDP 
legislators who voted against the package in defiance of the 
party leadership, and did not exclude the possibility that the 
legislators may be expelled from the party. It also recommended 
that Yutaka Shitoma, one of the rebels and the head of the 
party's election committee, give up his seat on the central 
executive committee, the officials said. 
  The House of Councillors dismissed the government package 
with 130 to 118 votes mainly due to the unexpectedly high number 
of SDP dissidents which substantially outnumbered the five LDP 
members who crossed party lines to vote for the bills. SDP 
Chairman Tomiichi Murayama, speaking at the central executive 
committee session, acknowledged the SDP's responsibility for the 
defeat of the reform bills and said, "We firmly support the 
coalition government, and want to live up to our 
responsibilities by tackling the remaining problems." 
  Many political sources have expected the party leadership to 
resign sooner or later because of failure to unite its members 
behind the government bills. 

</TEXT>

