<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   More Reaction to Political Reform Bill Rejection </TI></H3>
<H4>   Hata Said Optimistic About Bills </H4>
<F P=102> OW2401083294 Tokyo KYODO in English 0818 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2401083294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 24 KYODO -- Deputy Prime Minister and 
Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata voiced optimism Monday [24 
January] that the government can secure Diet approval for 
political reform bills before the current session ends Saturday. 
"I think the political reform bills are sure to be passed by 
the Diet because there are still opportunities for 
negotiations," Hata told a meeting with business executives at a 
Tokyo hotel. 
  Hata, who is also head of Shinseito (Japan Renewal Party), 
said the package can still be approved either by a joint panel 
of both houses of the Diet or by a two-thirds majority at the 
House of Representatives. 
  The House of Councillors rejected the package of four bills 
Friday. Seventeen rebel members of the Social Democratic Party 
(SDP), the largest force in the ruling coalition, joined members 
of the opposition Liberal Democratic Party and Japanese 
Communist Party to vote down the package. 
  Hata said the enactment of the four reform bills, which 
would 
introduce a new election system and measures designed to curtail 
corruption, would produce "dynamism" in Japanese politics 
because it would activate stalled debates in the Diet. He 
brushed aside suggestions for corruption prevention measures to 
be enacted before overall political reform, saying the root of 
political corruption lies in the current multiseat constituency 
system. 
  Touching on the sluggish economy, Hata predicted that the 
future of Japan's economy is not so gloomy, although it is 
unlikely to recover immediately. He told the audience of 
executives and managers from across Japan that compiling of the 
state budget and carrying out deregulations are essential for 
the economy, saying it would boost demand in Japan, open markets 
for other countries and improve public life. 
  The foreign minister expressed willingness for Japan to 
become a permanent member of the United Nations Security 
Council, saying Japan has various techniques and know-how to 
offer to the world besides money and that its role is to extend 
them to the world. Hata said Japan should take initiatives on 
the international scene and put forward its own proposals. 

</TEXT>

