<H3> <TI>   More Reaction to Political Reform Bill Rejection </TI></H3>
<H4>   SDPJ `Ready' To Hold Summit </H4>
<F P=102> OW2401084194 Tokyo KYODO in English 0827 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2401084194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 24 KYODO -- The Social Democratic 
Party (SDP) [of Japan, SDPJ], the largest among seven parties in 
the ruling coalition, said Monday [24 January] it is ready to 
accept a call from the main opposition party to hold summit 
talks between their heads over the political reform process. 
  SDP Chairman Tomiichi Murayama told a meeting with labor 
leaders Monday that he received an informal call for a summit 
between him and Yohei Kono, president of the Liberal Democratic 
Party (LDP). In the meeting, Murayama indicated that the SDP 
alone cannot strike a compromise over the matter noting the 
party is one of seven partners in the coalition, SDP officials 
said. 
  LDP Secretary General Yoshiro Mori earlier proposed holding 
talks between Kono and Murayama. 
  The MAINICHI SHIMBUN reported Monday that Kono and Murayama 
should have summit talks and agree to consider legislating an 
antigraft law separate from election reform bills. The national 
daily said if the country's two largest parties agree on placing 
priority on anticorruption measures, it will have a significant 
impact in resolving the impasse over political reform. 
  Last week, the House of Councillors voted down a package of 
four government-sponsored political reform bills which had 
passed the House of Representatives in November. 
  Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa and his ruling coalition 
are 
seeking to establish a joint panel of the two houses in a 
last-ditch effort to achieve political reform by Saturday, when 
the current session of the Diet ends. The political reform 
package is designed to introduce a combination of single-seat 
and proportional representation seats for lower house general 
elections, replacing the current multiseat district system, as 
well as stepping up controls on political fund-raising 
activities. 

</TEXT>

