<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   More Reaction to Political Reform Bill Rejection </TI></H3>
<H4>   Political Reform `Key' to Economy </H4>
<F P=102> OW2401075394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0746 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2401075394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 24 KYODO -- Six cabinet ministers 
shared the view Monday [24 January] that political reform is a 
key vehicle to jacking up the economy, a cabinet spokesman said 
Monday. "They agree that a major premise for making decisions 
on important economy-related policies hinges on achieving 
political reform," Deputy Chief Cabinet Secretary Nobuo Ishihara 
told a news conference. 
  "They confirmed that seeing through the political reform 
package is one of the best economy-spurring measures," he said. 
  The six cabinet ministers made their views known at a 
meeting 
held at Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa's official residence. 
They are all government members of an economic panel that 
advises the seven parties in the ruling coalition. 
  The six are Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata, Chief Cabinet 
Secretary Masayoshi Takemura, Finance Minister Hirohisa Fujii, 
International Trade and Industry Minister Hiroshi Kumagai, 
Economic Planning Agency Director General Manae Kubota and Home 
Affairs Minister Kanju Sato. 
  During the meeting, the ministers agreed that the next 15 
months are vital to getting the economy back on its feet in 1994 
and ensuring stable growth in 1995 and beyond, Ishihara said. 
The six did not discuss when additional pump-priming measures 
will be worked out and the national budget for fiscal 1994, 
starting April 1, will be formulated, he said. 

</TEXT>

