<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   More Reaction to Political Reform Bill Rejection </TI></H3>
<H4>   Two Houses' Joint Council Planned </H4>
<F P=102> OW2401074494 Tokyo KYODO in English 0711 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2401074494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 24 KYODO -- The Diet will set up a 
joint council of its two houses Tuesday in a last-ditch effort 
to enact a political reform package that was killed last week by 
the House of Councillors, political sources said Monday [24 
January]. Ruling coalition and opposition parties are expected 
to agree on the setting up the 20-member joint council at a 
meeting Monday night of the House of Representatives steering 
committee, they said. 
  The House of Representatives will approve the establishment 
of the panel at a plenary session Tuesday. The council will be 
formed by 10 members each from both houses. 
  The House of Representatives, which approved the bills in 
November, will select its 10 members from among those who voted 
for them. The House of Councillors will send 10 members from 
among those who voted against the bills. 
  If two-thirds of the joint panel members agree on a 
compromise plan, the four bills can be enacted into law once 
they are endorsed by a majority of votes at plenary sessions of 
both houses of the Diet. 
  Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa, who has said he would take 
political responsibility if he fails to get the package passed, 
will put the bills to a floor vote again at a lower house 
plenary session if the joint council ends in failure, coalition 
officials said. 
  Hosokawa explained his strategy during a meeting Monday of 
representatives from parties in his ruling coalition. The prime 
minister told the session that he is ready to meet Yohei Kono, 
president of the opposition Liberal Democratic Party [LDP], if 
Kono makes such a call. 
  Chief Cabinet Secretary Masayoshi Takemura told a morning 
news conference that both the ruling and opposition camps need 
to hold frank talks and work out a compromise. 
  LDP Diet Affairs Committee Chairman Sadatoshi Ozato told 
reporters the coalition parties should unify their position and 
promise not to take a vote at the lower house plenary session 
even if talks at the joint panel fail. Under constitutional 
rules, bills which were approved by the lower house but 
rejected by the upper chamber can be revived for legislation if 
the lower house passes it again by a two-thirds majority. 
  The upper house voted down the package of four 
government-sponsored reform bills which among other things call 
for the introduction of a combination of single-seat and 
proportional representation districts for lower house general 
elections in place of multiseat constituencies. The reform 
bills also aim to tighten controls on political fund-raising to 
stem graft. 
  Seventeen legislators of the Social Democratic Party (SDP), 
the largest coalition bloc, sided with LDP members to reject the 
bills. 
  At a meeting Monday, leaders of seven parties in the ruling 
coalition renewed their resolve to pursue enactment of political 
reform by the end of the current Diet session, the officials 
said. 
  The coalition is determined to enact the bills as a package 
that encompasses antigraft measures, the officials said. The 
political reform bills will only be effective to wipe out 
corruption if they are enacted as a package, the officials said. 
  The 90-day schedule of the present extraordinary Diet 
session 
was extended for 45 days beyond the initial deadline on December 
15 to achieve Hosokawa's pledge to act on political reform bills 
during the current parliamentary session. The Diet session ends 
Saturday. 
  Since taking office in August after ousting the LDP from its 
38-year grip on power, Hosokawa has staked his political fate on 
enacting political reform. 
  In the wake of Japan's political turbulence, Tokyo stock 
prices plunged sharply with the 225-issue Nikkei stock average 
plummeting 954.19 points to finish at 18,353.24. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

