<H3> <TI>   More Reaction to Political Reform Bill Rejection </TI></H3>
<H4>   Hosokawa Comments Further </H4>
<F P=102> OW2401043794 Tokyo KYODO in English 0428 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2401043794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 24 KYODO -- Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa will seek approval of a package of political reform 
bills at a House of Representatives plenary session if 
negotiations at a joint committee of both houses fail, officials 
said Monday [24 January]. Hosokawa made this clear at a meeting 
of representatives from parties in the ruling coalition, the 
officials said. 
  The package, which was rejected by a margin of 12 votes by 
the House of Councillors on Friday, can be enacted if it is 
passed again by a two-thirds majority in the lower house. The 
bills also could be enacted if a joint committee of 10 members 
each from both houses works out a compromise and wins approval 
by a majority vote from the two houses. 

