<H3> <TI>   More Reaction to Political Reform Bill Rejection </TI></H3>
<H4>   LDP Agrees To Setting Up Panel </H4>
<F P=102> OW2401030894 Tokyo KYODO in English 0257 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2401030894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 24 KYODO -- The main opposition 
Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) decided Monday [24 January] to 
agree to the setting up of a joint committee of both houses of 
the Diet to discuss modifications to a package of political 
reform bills. The government was defeated over the package last 
Friday, when it was rejected by the House of Councillors. 
  The LDP's decision to allow the matter to go before a Diet 
panel was reached by party President Yohei Kono and Secretary 
General Yoshiro Mori, the officials said. 
  The crucial package, on which Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa has staked his job, could still be enacted if the panel 
of 10 members from each of the two houses worked out a 
compromise that then won approval by a majority vote in both 
houses. The package rejected Friday had already been approved 
by the more powerful House of Representatives. 

</TEXT>

