<H3> <TI>   Former Komeito Member Questioned on Recruit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2001054594 Tokyo KYODO in English 0528 GMT 20 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2001054594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 20 KYODO -- A former Diet member of 
Komeito was questioned in court Thursday [20 January] as the 
first of two politicians indicted in the 1989 Recruit 
stocks-for-favors scandal. 
  Katsuya Ikeda, 56, a former House of Representatives 
legislator of Komeito, which is now in the ruling coalition, was 
questioned by his defense council and prosecutors at the Tokyo 
District Court about his alleged involvement in the scandal. He 
denied all the charges against him. 
  In May 1989, prosecutors indicted Ikeda without arresting 
him, on charges of receiving 5,000 unlisted shares of Recruit 
Cosmos, a real estate company, and 7 million yen in cash from 
Hiromasa Ezoe, founder and then chairman of Recruit Co., a major 
publisher of job information magazines, in September 1986. The 
shares appreciated considerably after being listed. 
  Ikeda is accused of taking the shares and the money in 
return 
for acting on the firm's behalf in the Diet in 1984 and 1985, 
when a "gentlemen's agreement" that companies fix the date to 
recruit university graduates was on the verge of becoming a 
titular accord. 
  Ikeda said his Diet questioning was not done on behalf of 
the 
firm. 
  In response to his defense council's questioning on the 
issue, Ikeda said he already had an interest in problems of job 
placement for university students before he was asked by Recruit 
to bring up the issue in the Diet as asserted by prosecutors. 
  Ikeda said he began to have an interest in the job placement 
accord around 1977 just after becoming a member of the lower 
house and had a recognition the accord would be difficult to 
observe. 
  Along with Ikeda, then Chief Cabinet Secretary Takao 
Fujinami 
of the then ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP), was indicted 
in the influence-peddling scandal. 
  Fujinami is being tried on charges of receiving Recruit 
Cosmos shares before their flotation as a bribe from Ezoe, 57, 
for similar favors to the firm. 
  The stocks-for-favors scandal involved secretaries or 
relatives of LDP heavyweights such as former Premiers Yasuhiro 
Nakasone, Noboru Takeshita, Kiichi Miyazawa and former Foreign 
Minister Michio Watanabe. 
  Takeshita, then prime minister, and Miyazawa, then finance 
minister, were forced to resign because of the scandal. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

