<H3> <TI>   Saito Sees Stimulus Package by 11 Feb Summit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2401094194 Tokyo KYODO in English 0933 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2401094194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 24 KYODO -- The government is expected 
to work out its new economic stimulus package in time before the 
Japan-U.S. summit in Washington on February 11, a top Finance 
Ministry official said Monday [24 January]. Vice Finance 
Minister Jiro Saito told a regular press meeting that it is the 
common view that the package would be in place before the 
summit, referring to early comments by Vice Trade Minister 
Hideaki Kumano calling for the launching by the summit. 
  Saito brushed aside the income tax cut issue, saying, "it 
will be decided by the economic problem forum" of the government 
and coalition parties. 
  Noting that the third extra budget for fiscal 1993 and the 
fiscal 1994 budget are to follow the package, Saito said he 
hopes the political turmoil would subside to allow "various 
measures as soon as possible." 
  Saito said the plunge in stock prices "stems from political 
uncertainties and other factors." But he rejected any effects 
from a possible delay in the economic package and budget. 
  "We have never mentioned a date to compile the budget," he 
said, adding the package was not slated for release on the day 
and the failure of the political reform bills to pass the upper 
house of the Diet came only last Friday. 
  Economic Planning Agency head Manae Kubota also said the 
implementation of economic stimulus measures by the government 
may be delayed until next month due to political uncertainty. 
  Kubota told a news conference that parties in the ruling 
coalition have already reached a broad agreement on the contents 
of the economic package, except income tax cuts. The income tax 
reduction, however, is an important pillar of the package and it 
should not be excluded from the program, she said. 
  She said political reforms must be implemented at all costs 
because the issue will be a major driving force for economic 
recovery. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

