<F P=103> OW2401041294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 24 KYODO -- Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokwawa seemed unconcerned about the stock market tumble 
Monday [24 January] morning, saying the prices will go up again. 
  Hosokawa said the effect on the stock market of the 
government's defeat on political reform was not a major problem. 
"(The stock prices) will move up again," he said. 
  Hosokawa noted that the Nikkei index recently fell to around 
16,000. The Nikkei stock average -- a key market indicator -- 
plunged 836.18 points to close the morning session at 18,471.25 
in response to the failure Friday of the coalition government's 
political reform package in the House of Councillors. 

