<F P=100> Philippines </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Suspected' Communists Burn Passenger Bus </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK2401032494 Manila PHILIPPINE DAILY INQUIRER in English 19 
Jan 94 p 1 </F>

<F P=103> BK2401032494 </F>
<F P=104>  Manila PHILIPPINE DAILY INQUIRER </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Charlie C. Senase] </F>
  [Excerpt] Cotabato City -- Suspected communist rebels 
torched a passenger bus in Maasim, Sarangani, on Monday after 
the bus firm refused to pay "revolutionary tax," police said 
yesterday. 
  Senior Superintendent Jovito Sales, police director for 
Central Mindanao, said the bus of the Yellow Bus Line (YBL) was 
travelling from Kiamba, Sarangani, to General Santos City when 
it was blocked by about a dozen suspected New People's Army 
(NPA) guerrillas. Thirty of their comrades served as lookouts 
near the highway, police said. 
  The armed men ordered all passengers to alight and bring 
with 
them their belongings, witnesses told police. 
  They then poured gasoline all over the vehicle before 
setting 
it on fire. 
  No one was hurt or molested, police said. 
  Yellow Bus Line plies routes in South Cotabato, Sultan 
Kudarat, North Cotabato, Bukidnon and Davao. 
  Sales said the YBL management, prior to the incident, had 
received notes and letters demanding that the company pay 
"revolutionary tax" to the communist rebels. [passage omitted 
on unrelated road accident] 

</TEXT>

