<F P=100> AUSTRALASIA </F>
<F P=101> Fiji </F>
<H3> <TI>   Parliament Dismissed; Elections Slated 18-25 Feb </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK2001094694 Hong Kong AFP in English 0935 GMT 20 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> BK2001094694 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Suva, Jan 20 (AFP) -- Fijian President Ratu Sir 
Kamisese Mara has officially dismissed parliament and announced 
national elections to be held from February 18 to 25. 
  "The president has advised the prime minister, the 
honourable 
Major General (Sitiveni) Rabuka, of his decision," a government 
statement said Wednesday. 
  Rabuka called for the dissolution of parliament when his 
budget was defeated November 29 by seven dissident members of 
government who voted against it in the House of Representatives. 
  Dominance of the ruling Fijian Political Party has been 
challenged by a breakaway party, the Fijian Association, which 
is led by former deputy prime minister Josevata Kamikamica. 
  Fiji's 1990 constitution gives indigenous Fijians the right 
to hold the premiership and a guaranteed 37 seats in the 70-seat 
lower house. 
  Indian Fijians have 27 seats, other races have five and the 
Polynesian island of Rotuma has one. 
  Polling is spread over a week to allow for voting in 
outlying 
Fijian islands. 

</TEXT>

