<F P=100> Vietnam </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reports on National Party Conference Continue </TI></H3>
<H4>   Delegates Discuss Do Muoi Report </H4>
<F P=102> BK2201100694 Hanoi VNA in English 0544 GMT 22 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> BK2201100694 </F>
<F P=104>  Hanoi VNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Hanoi VNA Jan. 22. -- Delegates at the mid-term 
conference of the Communist Party of Vietnam (CPV) on Jan. 20 
and 21 discussed the political report delivered by Party General 
Secretary Do Muoi. 
  The delegates focused on analyzing the all-sided 
achievements 
recorded over the past two years and a half and the most 
important, urgent issues in order to implement the resolutions 
of the seventh party congress. 
  They also analyzed opportunities and challenges, advantages 
and disadvantages at home and in international relations the 
party and the entire people are facing, thus defining premises 
for gradually introducing the country into a new stage of 
development, that of industrialization and modernization. The 
delegates paid great attention to the goals and concrete steps 
to be taken, especially measures and capacity to mobilize 
resources for the construction of socio-economic infrastructure 
to meet both long-oerm and short-term demands. 
  Many delegates showed their attention to the role of state 
management in the market economy, and methods for managing 
state-run businesses to ensure their leading position in key 
branches of the national economy. 
  Social and cultural issues were enthusiastically discussed. 
The anti-corruption and smuggling work was also analyzed and 
criticized seriously. Debates also concentrated on how to train 
purify and develop the contingent of the party members to meet 
the demand of the party leadership in the current process of 
innovation. 
  Today, the delegates will continue their discussion of the 
political report. 

</TEXT>

