<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Asked To Muster PRC Aid on Nuclear Issue </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2401080494 Seoul YONHAP in English 0749 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2401080494 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Jan. 24 (YONHAP) -- South Korea asked the 
United States Monday to muster Chinese help in solving North 
Korea's nuclear problem. 
  Foreign Minister Han Sung-chu met with visiting Deputy 
Assistant U.S. Secretary of State Tom Hubbard and shared 
concern that North Korea not be allowed to delay much longer in 
inspection negotiations with the International Atomic Energy 
Agency (IAEA). He asked that U.S. Secretary of State Warren 
Christopher ask China to exert active influence on North Korea 
on the nuclear issue, Chang Chae-yong, director-general of the 
American Affairs Bureau at the Foreign Ministry, said in the 
post-meeting briefing. 
  Christopher and his Chinese counterpart, Qian Qichen, are 
due 
to meet in Paris this week. 
  Hubbard had come to Seoul Sunday after accompanying Treasury 
Secretary Lloyd Bentsen on an Asian tour. He is the top U.S. 
representative to regular contacts with North Korea in New York. 
  The U.S. official worried at the delay in North Korea-U.S. 
inspection talks and declared there will be no negotiations of 
any sort between North Korea and the United States without the 
Pyongyang-IAEA agreement first. 
  Hubbard called China's role so far as having been 
constructive and promised to seek Beijing's powerful influence 
on North Korea at the Paris meeting of the foreign ministers. 
  Hubbard left for Washington after afternoon talks with South 
Korean Nuclear Ambassador Kim Sam-hun and chief Presidential 
Aide for Diplomacy and National Security Chong Chong-uk. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-48167 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas015_d_94003" </HT>


