<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Asks for Cattle, Beef Market Opening </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2001063194 Seoul CHOSON ILBO in Korean 20 Jan 94 p 10 </F>
<F P=103> SK2001063194 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul CHOSON ILBO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Korean </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The United States has asked the ROK to open its 
cattle market in addition to its beef market by applying an 
import quota system and to allow local meat-processing firms to 
sell imported beef by processing it as packaged beef. 
  In the two-day livestock negotiations with the ROK in 
Washington on 19 January, the United States demanded that the 
ROK ensure that apart from beef, a minimum volume of cattle, be 
imported each year since the General Agreement on Tariffs and 
Trade [GATT] schedule of concessions provide for zero percent 
tariff for cattle and since the cattle market is to open from 1 
July 1997. The United States also requested that the ROK ease 
its government restrictions prohibiting the local 
meet-processing firms from processing and selling beef imported 
through the simultaneous buying and selling system (SBS) as 
packaged beef. 
  The ROK side, however, is reported to have told the U.S. 
side 
that it is difficult for the ROK to set quotas on live cattle 
and that for the time being, the ROK has to maintain 
restrictions on the sale of packaged meat by meat-processing 
firms that are members of consumer organizations. Participating 
as senior delegates in the Washington negotiation were Yi 
Yong-nae, agricultural attache of the ROK Embassy in the United 
States from the ROK side and Jim Grueff, chief of the Uruguay 
Round [Multilateral Trade Policy Affairs] section of the 
Agricultural Department from the U.S. side. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-48168 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas015_d_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-015 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  25 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Renegotiation With U.S. on Uruguay Round Urged </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2001011094 Seoul THE KOREA TIMES in English 20 Jan 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> SK2001011094 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul THE KOREA TIMES </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Some scholars and lawmakers yesterday called for 
renegotiation of the Uruguay Round [UR] talks with the United 
States in the agricultural field, mainly in relation to the 
opening of the domestic rice market. 
  In a policy debate over the multilateral UR negotiations 
organized by the opposition Democratic Party [DP], they also 
called on the National Assembly to oppose ratification of the UR 
negotiations and the people to stage a nationwide campaign to 
deter the pressure to import rice. 
  Prof. Kim Wan-pae of Chungang University said, "We should 
not 
submit the documents pledging to carry out the opening of 
agricultural and livestock product markets until late February, 
the deadline set by the GATT [General Agreement on Tariffs and 
Trade]." 
  "We have to appeal to the GATT and ask for more negotiations 
with the United States," he added. 
  He called on the government to ask the GATT to acknowledge 
trade between South and North Korea as an internal exchange 
between the same people. 
  "We need to resume negotiation with the United States 
because 
it is attempting to reject the imports of some agricultural and 
livestock materials to protect its domestic market," he added. 
  He asserted the Assembly special committee on UR 
negotiations 
needs to be operated constantly in a bid to come forward with 
effective measures in this connection. 
  He also called for revolutionary changes in the rural 
structure to ride the expected tough UR wave. 
  Prof. Kim Su-haeng of the Seoul National University said the 
government must reflect the interests of the people in all 
sectors of society in the pursuit of its internationalization. 
  "The government did nothing in connection with the 
improvement of the welfare of the underprivileged, only putting 
emphasis on strengthening the national competitiveness in 
international society," he said. 
  "In a sense, further globalization will result in 
destitution 
of agricultural areas and the increase of jobless people due to 
the rapid change of industrial structure toward autonomization," 
he added. 
  Cho Sung-u from the national emergency committee to protect 
the rice market said, "The UR talks have yet to be finalized. 
It is not true that the opening of the markets for basic 
agricultural products including rice is inevitable." 
  "We have to embark on a national campaign to block rice 
imports by collecting signatures and money to this end," he 
added. 
  Rep. Kim Yong-chin of the DP said, "As an initial step in 
the 
UR talks, we have to call on the U.S. to resume negotiation and 
to clarify our objections to the rice import." 
  Kim called for maintaining the production of rice and other 
basic agricultural products at a proper level to prepare for the 
upcoming national unification era, and other short and long term 
developments. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

