<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   ROK Scientist Appointed to IAEA Advisory Group </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2401012994 Seoul YONHAP in English 0122 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2401012994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Jan. 24 (YONHAP) -- A South Korean nuclear 
scientist was recently appointed to the Standing Advisory Group 
on Safeguards and Implementation (SAGSI) of the International 
Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA), the Foreign Ministry said Monday. 
  Hans Blix, director-general of the IAEA, announced the 
appointment of Dr. Kim Pyong-ku, 50, vice president of the Korea 
Atomic Energy Research Institute [KAERI], Foreign Ministry 
officials said. 
  The SAGSI, consisting of 14 regular members, is an 
influential advisory group to the IAEA director for the 
formation of policy and execution of policy and projects aimed 
at preventing proliferation of nuclear arms and promotion of the 
peaceful use of nuclear energy. 
  Kim, the first Korean to be appointed a SAGSI member, is a 
graduate of Seoul National University and California Institute 
of Technology. He worked as a regular researcher at the jet 
propulsion laboratory in the United States between 1972 and 1975 
before returning home to work for the KAERI in May 1975. 

</TEXT>

