<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yi Ki-taek To Talk With ROK on Visiting DPRK </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1701020394 Seoul YONHAP in English 0134 GMT 17 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1701020394 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Jan. 17 (YONHAP) -- Opposition leader Yi 
Ki-taek said Monday he will negotiate with the government on 
visiting North Korea after the National Assembly session ends 
next month. 
  He told reporters at his home early in the morning that he 
had been considering a North Korea visit "from quite long ago." 
  Aware of the criticism that he is acting on a whim, the 
opposition leader said he had been discussing inter-Korean 
relations with experts. 
  "I sought the opinions of others whom I met at last year-end 
gatherings and they had rather progressive views about even the 
nuclear problem," Yi said. 
  Asked whether arrangements for the visit are well in 
advance, 
he said they "have just begun." 
  "I expressed my intent to go to North Korea as an opposition 
leader, and I am preparing and collecting necessary materials," 
Yi said. 
  He will begin consultations with the government about the 
visit after the extraordinary assembly session in January and 
February, and has specifically ordered his spokesman to announce 
that he will not, under any circumstances, neglect domestic 
issues such as water contamination and the Uruguay Round, Yi 
said. 
  As he was doing it for improvement of inter-Korean ties, 
there was "no reason" for the government to refuse him 
permission to make the trip, Yi said. 
  The opposition leader embarks on a visit to China later this 
month that was originally planned for last November or December. 
  Meetings with Chinese leaders were set then, but 
rescheduling 
is not going well, he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-48180 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas015_d_94016" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-015 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  25 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   DP Leader To Seek Permission for DPRK Visit in Feb </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1701083994 Seoul YONHAP in English 0727 GMT 17 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1701083994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Jan. 17 (YONHAP) -- Yi Ki-taek, chairman of 
the major opposition Democratic Party, has said that he will 
formally apply in February for a government permit to visit 
North Korea. 
  Yi, exchanging New Year's greetings with Stephen Cardinal 
Kim 
Su- hwan at Myongdong Cathedral, said Monday [17 January] he 
will propose an inter-Korean summit and a tripartite meeting of 
Pyongyang, Washington and Seoul if he meets with North Korean 
President Kim Il-song. 
  Frequent inter-Korean exchanges, including cultural 
exchanges 
and economic cooperation, will help resolve inter-Korean 
problems and achieve national reunification, he told the Roman 
Catholic primate of South Korea. 
  "My reason for visiting North Korea is that we remain in the 
cold-war framework of reasoning, though we are living in the 
post- cold war era," Yi said. 
  "The political approach to the reunification issue so far 
should now be shifted to an economic approach, and I believe the 
opposition party has a role to play in creating an environment 
for such a shift and in arranging inter-Korean talks for 
solution of the nuclear issue." 
  The cardinal said visiting North Korea is not always as 
simple as Yi made out because North Korea may try to make use of 
such a visit for its own political objectives. 

</TEXT>

