<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Businessmen To Visit if North Allows Inspections </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1901045094 Seoul MAEIL KYONGJE SINMUN in Korean 19 Jan 94 
p 2 </F>

<F P=103> SK1901045094 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul MAEIL KYONGJE SINMUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Korean </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] If North Korea allows the International Atomic 
Energy Agency [IAEA] to inspect seven reported nuclear 
facilities and agrees to hold the exchange of special envoys of 
the South and North, the government will allow businessmen to 
visit North Korea. 
  A government official revealed on 18 January: "If North 
Korea allows the IAEA inspection team to visit North Korea to 
receive practical [silchilchokin] inspection of the seven 
reported facilities and agrees to the exchange of special envoys 
of the South and North, this will be recognized as a 
breakthrough in resolving the nuclear issue, thus making it 
possible to allow businessmen to visit North Korea." 
  This greatly eases the government's policy that was decided 
upon at the August reunification-related ministers meeting in 
which it decided that `businessmen will be allowed to visit 
North Korea only when North Korea completely returns to the 
Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty and agrees to the inspection of 
unreported facilities in Yongbyon.' 
  If a breakthrough is made on the nuclear issue, the 
government plans to allow technicians to visit North Korea to 
activate the consignment processing trade [imgagong kyoyok]. 
  A government official said: "The volume of South-North trade 
was reduced by six percent last year because of the nuclear 
issue. However, processing trade for reexport [witak kagong] 
increased by seven to eight times, thus showing the possibility 
of South-North trade. Necessary measures will be taken at the 
government level this year to actively assist such processing." 
  If North Korea accepts the IAEA's inspection and also the 
South-North mutual inspection, the government will actively work 
on opening direct South-North sea route which is being pointed 
out as the greatest obstacle in South-North trade. The 
government will also establish a South-North exchange 
cooperative subcommittee to provide measures for guaranteeing 
investment, preventing double taxation, and providing procedures 
for disputes. 
  It was learned that the sea routes between Inchon Port-Nampo 
Port, Pusan Port-Wonsan Port, and Pohang Port-Chongjin Port will 
be the most likely sea routes already agreed upon between South 
and North Korea in case a direct sea route is established. 
  The government plans to make a final decision over this 
matter at the 25 January reunification-related ministers meeting. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

