<F P=102>  SK2001113394 Seoul YONHAP in English 1040 GMT 20 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2001113394 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Jan. 20 (YONHAP) -- Lin Tsung-hsien, chief of 
the Taiwanese mission in Seoul, flew into Seoul on Thursday 
afternoon to assume his new duty. 
  "I will do all I can to restore the suspended bilateral 
relations at an early date and promote new relationship based on 
the principles of reciprocity and equality," Lin said on arrival 
at Kimpo Airport. 
  He said closer cooperation between the two countries will 
serve mutual interests and also contribute to stability and 
prosperity in Asia. 
  South Korea and Taiwan severed formal diplomatic ties in 
August 1992 when Seoul entered ambassadorial relations with 
mainland China. 
  Late last year, the two countries agreed to exchange 
semiofficial resident missions. Seoul opened its mission in 
Taipei on last Nov. 25. 

