<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   ROK, Taiwan Tourist Exchange `To Regain Vigor' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2101035794 Seoul YONHAP in English 0235 GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2101035794 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Jan. 21 (YONHAP) -- Tourist exchanges with 
Taiwan are expected to regain vigor along with the inauguration 
of a Taiwanese mission in Seoul Monday, the Korea National 
Tourism Corp. (KNTC) and tourism sources said Friday. 
  Tourism will soon recover to the level of 1992, when Seoul 
and Taipei severed ties because of Seoul's normalization of ties 
with Beijing, they said. 
  The opening of the Taiwanese mission means that Taipei wants 
to increase personnel and material exchanges, they said, so 
Taiwanese travel agents are likely to start selling package 
tours to Seoul. 
  Last year, 147,000 Taiwanese nationals visited South Korea, 
or nearly half of the 296,000 recorded in 1992, and 85,000 
Koreans visited Taiwan, compared with 126,000. 
  With severance of ties, the national carriers of both 
countries cut flights between Seoul and Taipei on Sept. 15, 1992. 
  Korean Air and Asiana Airlines of Korea, and China Airlines 
and Eva Airlines of Taiwan are negotiating for resumption of 
flights. 
  Before severance of ties, Korean Air had 16 flights a week 
between Seoul and Taipei; Asiana, four; China Airlines, nine; 
and Eva, six. 
  Cathay Pacific Airlines, Northwest Airlines, Thai 
international Airways, Singapore Airlines and Delta Airlines 
currently have 34 direct flights a week between Seoul and Taipei. 
  Some travel agents that specialize in Taiwanese tourists 
have 
sales promotions. Taiwanese like to visit Korea in the winter 
for the snow-covered mountains and skiing, which are unavailable 
in Taiwan. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

