<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   ROK-PRC To Sign Aviation Agreement in Beijing </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2101025394 Seoul YONHAP in English 0137 GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2101025394 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Jan. 21 (YONHAP) -- South Korea and China are 
expected to sign an aviation agreement on direct services when 
President Kim Yong-sam visits Beijing in March, officials said 
Friday. 
  Working-level negotiations in the Chinese capital have been 
extended and are progressing in a "positive direction," one said. 
  Korea will succeed in having the Seoul-Beijing flight 
control 
transfer point set at 124 degrees longitude as designated by the 
International Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO). 
  China had been opposed, saying the line was drawn when 
Taiwan 
represented China at the ICAO. 
  But the two sides are to skirt the transfer point issue on 
the Seoul-Shanghai route and fly along a corridor, as done up to 
now, the official said. 
  Kim is expected to visit Beijing in March and the two 
countries likely will formally sign the aviation agreement then, 
he said. 
  The agreement will be initialed at the next aviation talks 
in 
Beijing. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

