<H3> <TI>   PKO Unit's Functions in Somalia Under Review </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1801104394 Seoul YONHAP in English 1022 GMT 18 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1801104394 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Jan. 18 (YONHAP) -- The duty and camp site 
of the South Korean engineer unit serving in Somalia as part of 
the U.N. Peace Keeping Forces [PKO], may be changed shortly, a 
Foreign Ministry official said on Tuesday. 
  The official said the likely refixing has been necessitated 
as the function of the U.N. PKO forces there has been reduced 
to relief programs only and major Western countries' troops are 
set to pull out of the African country shortly. 
  "In particular, we are discussing with the U.N. Secretariat 
and relevant countries on matters related to the security of the 
Korean PKO unit since the Italian contingent which has been 
supporting the Korean unit in terms of security is to return to 
Italy by the end of March," he said. 
  The official added that despite the planned early withdrawal 
of the troops of major Western countries, there is no plan so 
far to bring the Korean unit home ahead of schedule. 
  The Korean engineer unit is supposed to remain in Somalia 
through July this year. 

</TEXT>

