<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government To Enforce Financial Retrenchment Policy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1701112994 Seoul YONHAP in English 1029 GMT 17 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1701112994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Jan. 17 (YONHAP) -- The government has 
decided to operate this year's money supply tightly to an extent 
that does not pose an extra burden to industries. 
  Finance Minister Hong Chae-hyong said on Monday the money 
supply expansion ceiling has been set at 14 to 17 percent for 
this year. "Unlike past practices, however, we will operate 
money supply a little tightly without regard to the ceiling," 
Hong said. 
  In a policy consultation with senior Bank of Korea 
officials, 
the finance minister said, "Money supply should be operated in 
consideration of the trend of money interests in view of 
industries' financial burden." 
  Touching on the ceiling of foreigners' investment in stocks, 
Minister Hong said the government plans, if possible, to reduce 
the influx of foreign money into the stock market this year. 
  "We must develop mid- and long-term policy devices over this 
issue in consideration of our country's entry into the 
Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) 
next year," the minister said. 
  He thus implied that his Ministry would expand the ceiling 
of 
foreigners' investment in stocks by next year at the latest as 
planned. 
  "To open the stock market without developing devices for the 
management of money supply is like pushing a brakeless car down 
from the top of a hill," Hong said. "Yet, a winter comes anyway 
even though you didn't prepare a coat." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

