<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government To Keep `No Work, No Wage' Policy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1401122494 Seoul YONHAP in English 1123 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1401122494 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Jan. 14 (YONHAP) -- The government will 
strictly enforce the "no work, no wage" principle in future 
labor disputes, Labor Affairs Minister Nam Chae-hui said on 
Friday. 
  The principle calls for no remunerations for workers when 
they do not work during the period of labor disputes. 
  Minister Nam said another principle his ministry will uphold 
will be the policy that "essential matters related to rights to 
personnel and management cannot be subject to labor disputes." 
  In an exclusive interview with the YONHAP news agency, Nam 
said his ministry will abide by these principles if only to 
dispel confusion in labor-management negotiations this year. 
  "No work, no wage" policy is a general principle that has 
been broadly recognized around the world, he said. 
  As for disputes over personnel and management rights, the 
labor minister said that though the labor rights are guaranteed 
under the Constitution, they cannot infringe on the essential 
elements of other basic rights. 
  "Since the right to management is based on the right to 
properties guaranteed under the basic law, labor disputes aimed 
at interfering in management cannot be justified," Nam said. 
  He added, however, that in case matters falling under the 
realm of personnel or management rights have a serious effect 
directly on working conditions or the standing of workers, 
disputes could be justified only to such an extent. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-48210 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas015_d_94046" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-015 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  25 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   POSCO Labor, Management Settle on Wage Increase </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1901074494 Seoul YONHAP in English 0658 GMT 19 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1901074494 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Pohang, South Korea, Jan. 19 (YONHAP) -- Pohang 
Iron and Steel Co. Ltd. (POSCO) workers will get a 2.9-percent 
pay hike this month under an agreement thrashed out by the 
company's industrial council. 
  The modest increase in basic pay and fixed allowances was 
set 
by the council, which comprises 18 labor representatives and 12 
management negotiators, in a bid to maintain POSCO's 
international competitiveness, according to a company spokesman. 
  "The industrial council agreed that the pay raise should be 
low for the company to survive the rapidly changing 
circumstances of international business," he said. 
  POSCO's wage accord is expected to affect pay negotiations 
at 
other industrial companies in the Pohang region. 
  POSCO, which has some 22,622 workers, is the world's second 
biggest iron and steel maker with production last year estimated 
at 22.48 million tons. 

</TEXT>

