<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government May Grant Rights to Illegal Aliens </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1801095894 Seoul YONHAP in English 0800 GMT 18 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1801095894 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Jan. 18 (YONHAP) -- The government is giving 
serious consideration to guaranteeing illegal aliens the same 
treatment as Korean workers under the labor standard law and 
industrial accident insurance law. 
  The Korea Labor Institute (KLI) has recommended the step and 
Labor Minister Nam Chae-hui has approved it, KLI President Kim 
Tae-mo said Tuesday. 
  President Kim Yong-sam ordered humane treatment of illegal 
foreign workers Jan. 13, when the Labor Ministry reported on its 
new year agenda, and Nam instructed KLI to study the matter, Kim 
said. 
  The recommendation is based on Article 5 of the Labor 
Standard Law, which says that a foreign worker in the country 
and with a contract, even if it is illegal, cannot be treated 
unfairly on the basis of nationality or religion. 
  There are some 56,000 illegal alien workers in the country 
and most work for small- and medium-sized industrial companies. 
  It is KLI's argument that the government tacitly approved 
their contracts by overlooking their illegal presence and 
employment and it must therefore take the responsibility. 
  Before the Ministry can take any action, it must discuss the 
matter with the Justice Ministry, which opposes labor rights for 
illegal aliens under Article 15 of the Immigration Control Law, 
which says foreigners without residential qualifications as 
stated by the president may not be employed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

