<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government To Revive Labor Day To Ease Relations </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1401072594 Seoul YONHAP in English 0637 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1401072594 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Jan. 14 (YONHAP) -- Abolished in 1958, Labor 
Day will be celebrated in South Korea on May 1, 1995, for the 
first time in 36 years, the government and its party decided 
Friday. 
  Labor Minister Nam Chae-hui, Democratic Liberal Party [DLP] 
Director General of Policy Coordination Paek Nam-chi, and other 
government and DLP officials agreed to revive Labor Day but put 
off revision of the law for a year to reflect upon the position 
of employers. 
  The move to reform labor policy seems aimed at easing worker 
dissatisfaction on the eve of spring wage negotiations. 
  Dissident labor organizations, but not the Federation of 
Korean Trade Unions (FKTU), have asked for a revival of Labor 
Day for 36 years. FKTU, which stuck to Worker's Day (March 10), 
officially decided to ask for the return of Labor Day in 1990. 
  In spite of the delay, party officials say they expect the 
decision to revive Labor Day to be welcomed. 
  President Syngman Yi abolished Labor Day in 1958 and 
replaced 
it with March 10, anniversary of the founding of the right-wing 
predecessor of FKTU, as Worker's Day. 

</TEXT>

