<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry Studies Pensions for Farmers, Fishermen </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1401044494 Seoul YONHAP in English 0235 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1401044494 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Jan. 14 (YONHAP) -- The Ministry of Health 
and Social Affairs plans to introduce pensions for farmers and 
fishermen to compensate them for rice market opening, ministry 
officials said Friday. 
  The ministry will finalize the system by June and present 
its 
proposal to the National Assembly in autumn for introduction 
next year. 
  Businesses with more than five employees must join the 
national pension scheme. Contributions of 6 percent of wages 
are shared by the employee (4 percent) and his employer (2 
percent) according to the national pension law. 
  Anyone else who wants to join the system may, but they must 
pay all 6 percent themselves. 
  According to a tentative plan drawn up by the ministry, 
about 
995,000 households in farming and fishing villages and 650,000 
non-farming or fishing households in rural areas will be obliged 
to join the national pension scheme. 
  In rural areas, contributions and pensions will be paid on a 
per household basis instead of an individual basis. Pensions 
are payable from the 60th birthday of the head of the household. 
  An official said, however, that the ministry is still 
studying whether to share the contributions. 
  The government also has to decide what percent of income -- 
3 
percent or 6 percent -- rural people should pay toward their 
pensions. 

</TEXT>

