<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Opposition Leader Supports Realignment Proposal </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1401035994 Seoul YONHAP in English 0256 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1401035994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Jan. 14 (YONHAP) -- Opposition leader Yi 
Ki-taek openly threw his support behind realignment of local 
administrative units Friday, rekindling the talk of a massive 
rezoning that President Kim Yong-sam had silenced, though he 
said he was still opposed to dividing up the city of Seoul. 
  "We shouldn't blindly oppose it. We will review it," Yi 
said. 
  "Proposals for rezoning in the past were just gerrymandering 
before an election, but as long as it is conducted fairly, it's 
worth consideration," the Democratic Party leader said. 
  DP Spokesman Pak Chi-won confirmed Yi's remarks, saying the 
redistricting "should be done if necessary." 
  The realignment of administrative units would include 
merging 
cities and counties before the mayoral, gubernatorial and local 
elections in the first half of next year. 
  Stories were floated last week that the ruling party was 
ready to split up Seoul as well because it was concerned an 
opposition figure would be elected mayor, a position so powerful 
it is called the no. 2 post after the president, and hamper the 
administration. 
  President Kim immediately dismissed the idea, and Yi said 
Friday that Seoul "can never be" divided. 
  DP officials said a party leadership meeting early next week 
will formulate the party's official position on administrative 
redistricting. 

</TEXT>

