<H3> <TI>   `No Possibility' of Easing Restrictions on Hyundai </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1701095994 Seoul YONHAP in English 0818 GMT 17 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1701095994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Jan. 17 (YONHAP) -- The Hyundai Business 
Group is likely to continue to have a hard time obtaining 
assistance from Korea Development Bank [KDB] or other 
state-invested financial organizations as long as group founder 
Chong Chu-yong remains active in management of the conglomerate, 
a senior government source said Monday. 
  The government has reacted coolly to repeated calls for an 
easing of the financial restrictions from group management, the 
source said. 
  Hyundai Chairman Chong Se-yong, a younger brother of Chong, 
asked President Kim Yong-sam in their tete-a-tete in September 
for his help in having financial institutions resume financial 
assistance to Hyundai, and a similar appeal was made to Economic 
Planning Minister Chong Chae-sok last week, but to no avail, the 
source said. 
  Even close aides to the president and some cabinet ministers 
have tried to persuade Kim to ease the restrictions, but Kim has 
reportedly hinted that there is no possibility of the government 
relaxing its position with regard to Hyundai. 
  Hyundai's relations with the government soured so much after 
Chong entered politics two years ago that the group has 
continuously been excluded from the beneficiaries of KDB 
facility investment loans and other financial assistance. 

</TEXT>

