<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Currency Loans Extended to More Firms </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2101011894 Seoul THE KOREA HERALD in English 21 Jan 94 p 8 </F>
<F P=103> SK2101011894 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul THE KOREA HERALD </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The scope of businesses qualified for foreign 
currency loans will be extended to purchasers of airplanes and 
second-hand ships and small- and medium-sized companies which 
introduce high technologies from abroad, starting from today. 
  The Bank of Korea has revised foreign currency loan-related 
regulations in such a way as to expand foreign currency loans to 
enterprises in a bid to promote corporate facility investment 
and to lessen companies' financial burden, it said yesterday. 
  Under the revised regulations, the ratio of foreign currency 
loans extended to businesses has been raised. The foreign 
currency ratio for large-sized manufacturers which import 
facility equipment will be raised from 80 percent of import 
prices to 90 percent and for small-sized companies, from 90 to 
100 percent. 
  The comparable ratio for enterprises which seek direct 
investment abroad will also be raised by 10 percentage points to 
70 percent of the invested fund for large companies and by 10 
percentage points to 80 percent for small companies. 
  Along with this, a maximum maturity for foreign currency 
loans will be extended from the current eight years to 10 years, 
considering long-term fund demands such as importers of plants 
or airplanes, the central bank said. 
  The central bank also abolished regulation requiring 
domestic 
businesses to acquire prior recommendation from the Ministry of 
Industry, Trade and Energy when they import facility equipment 
from Japan. 
  In the past, the recommendation system was introduced to 
curb 
excessive imports of various facility equipment, including 
machinery. 
  The central bank also allowed foreign currency-dealing banks 
to have a free hand in determining grace periods and repayment 
methods of foreign currency loans raised by themselves. 
  Meanwhile, the central bank plans to provide $3 billion out 
of its foreign reserve holdings to foreign currency banks in the 
first half of the year. 
  Now, the central bank is offering foreign currency funds at 
Libor (London Inter-Bank Offered Rate) to foreign currency banks 
which in turn loan the funds to enterprises at an annual rate of 
0.5-1.0 percent above Libor. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-48223 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas015_d_94059" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-015 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  25 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

