<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Institute on Competitiveness in Shipbuilding </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2001041594 Seoul YONHAP in English 0036 GMT 20 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2001041594 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Jan. 20 (YONHAP) -- South Korea's 
shipbuilding industry is expected to maintain its competitive 
edge over Japan as long as there is no great change in foreign 
exchange rates. 
  The prediction is based on the facts that Korean 
shipbuilders 
can undercut Japanese-built ship prices while they can compete 
against the Japanese in quality and marketing, according to a 
report issued Thursday by the Korea Institute for Industrial 
Economy and Trade. 
  The report said the general technological level of Korean 
shipbuilders is below that of the Japanese, but the quality of 
products, marketing and after-sales service are almost on a par 
with the Japanese. 
  In price competition, however, Korean yards are far ahead of 
the Japanese, offsetting their weak points, it said. Especially 
because of the rising value of the yen from last year, their 
competitive power has continued to rise. 
  As a result, Korean shipbuilders are expected to maintain 
their edge over their Japanese counterparts as long as the 
foreign exchange trend keeps up, it said. 
  Against Chinese shipbuilders, meanwhile, the Koreans lag 
slightly behind in price competitiveness but Korea far outpaces 
China in all other aspects including technology, marketing, 
financing, after- sales service and marketing, it said. 
  Compared with European shipyards, it said, Korean 
shipbuilders are far ahead. In other aspects, they are either 
on a par or slightly ahead of European builders, it added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

